#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:64
msgid "File Format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:66
msgid ""
"There  must be whitespace between keywords. Attribute keywords end with a"
" colon ``':'``. An attribute is followed by its containing attributes, or"
" a value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:69
msgid ""
"At the top  level only **server:**, **key:**, **pattern:**, **zone:**, "
"**tls-auth:**, and **remote-control:** are allowed. These are followed by"
" their attributes or a new top-level keyword. The **zone:** attribute is "
"followed by zone options. The **server:** attribute is followed by global"
" options for the NSD server. A **key:** attribute is used to define keys "
"for authentication. The **pattern:** attribute is followed by the zone "
"options for zones  that use the pattern. A **tls-auth:** attribute is "
"used to define credentials for authenticating an outgoing TLS connection "
"used for XFR-over-TLS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:78
msgid ""
"Files can be included using the **include:** directive. It can appear "
"anywhere, and takes a single filename as an argument. Processing "
"continues as if the text from the included file was copied into the "
"config file at that point. If a chroot is used an absolute filename is "
"needed (with the chroot prepended), so that the include can be  parsed  "
"before and after application of the chroot (and the knowledge of what "
"that chroot is).  You can use ``'*'`` to include a wildcard match of "
"files,  e.g. :file:`foo/nsd.d/*.conf`. Also  ``'?'``, ``'{}'``, ``'[]'``,"
" and ``'~'`` work, see *glob(7)*. If no files match the pattern, this is "
"not an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:89
msgid "Server Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:91
msgid ""
"The global options (if not overridden from  the  NSD  commandline) are "
"taken from the **server:** clause. There may only be one **server:** "
"clause."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:115
msgid "ip-address: <ip4 or ip6>[@port] [servers] [bindtodevice] [setfib]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:95
msgid ""
"NSD  will  bind  to the listed ip-address. Can be given multiple times to"
" bind multiple ip-addresses. Optionally, a port number can be given. If "
"none are given NSD listens to the wildcard interface. Same as commandline"
" option :option:`-a`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:100
msgid ""
"To limit which NSD server(s)  listen  on  the  given  interface, specify "
"one or more  servers separated by whitespace after <ip>[@port]. Ranges "
"can be used as a shorthand to specify multiple consecutive servers. By "
"default every server will listen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:105
#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:516
msgid ""
"If an interface name is used instead of ip4 or ip6, the list of IP "
"addresses associated with that interface is picked up and used at server "
"start."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:109
msgid ""
"For servers with multiple IP addresses that can be used to send traffic "
"to the internet, list them one by one, or the source address of replies "
"could be wrong. This is because if the udp socket associates a source "
"address of ``0.0.0.0`` then the kernel picks an ip-address with which to "
"send to the internet, and it picks the wrong one. Typically needed for "
"anycast instances. Use ip-transparent to be able to list addresses that "
"turn on later (typical for certain load-balancing)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:118
msgid "interface: <ip4 or ip6>[@port] [servers] [bindtodevice] [setfib]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:118
msgid "Same as ip-address (for ease of compatibility with unbound.conf)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:124
msgid "ip-transparent: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:121
msgid ""
"Allows NSD to bind to non local addresses. This is useful to have NSD "
"listen to IP addresses that are not (yet) added to the network interface,"
" so that it can answer immediately when the address is added. Default is "
"no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:128
msgid "ip-freebind: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:127
msgid ""
"Set the IP_FREEBIND option to bind to nonlocal addresses and interfaces "
"that are down. Similar to ip-transparent. Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:136
msgid "reuseport: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:131
msgid ""
"Use the SO_REUSEPORT socket option, and create file descriptors for every"
" server in the server-count. This improves performance of the network "
"stack. Only really useful if you also configure a server-count higher "
"than 1 (such as, equal to the number of cpus). The default is no. It "
"works on Linux, but does not work on FreeBSD, and likely does not work on"
" other systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:140
msgid "send-buffer-size: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:139
msgid ""
"Set the send buffer size for query-servicing sockets. Set to 0 to use the"
" default settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:144
msgid "receive-buffer-size: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:143
msgid ""
"Set the receive buffer size for query-servicing sockets. Set to 0 to use "
"the default settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:151
msgid "debug-mode: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:147
msgid ""
"Turns on debugging mode for nsd, does not fork a daemon process. Default "
"is no. Same as commandline option :option:`-d`. If set to yes it does not"
" fork and stays in the foreground, which can be helpful for commandline "
"debugging, but is also used by certain server supervisor processes to "
"ascertain that the server is running."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:154
msgid "do-ip4: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:154
msgid "If yes, NSD listens to IPv4 connections. Default yes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:157
msgid "do-ip6: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:157
msgid "If yes, NSD listens to IPv6 connections. Default yes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:163
msgid "database: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:160
msgid ""
"By default '/var/db/nsd/nsd.db' is used. The specified file is used to "
"store the compiled zone information. Same as commandline option "
":option:`-f`. If set to ``\"\"`` then no database is used. This uses less"
" memory but zone updates are not (immediately) spooled to disk."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:170
msgid "zonelistfile: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:166
msgid ""
"By default :file:`/var/db/nsd/zone.list` is used. The specified file is "
"used to store the dynamically added list of zones. The list is written to"
" by NSD to add and delete zones. It is a text file with a zone-name and "
"pattern-name on each line. This file is used for the nsd-control addzone "
"and delzone commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:176
msgid "identity: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:173
msgid ""
"Returns the specified identity when asked for ``CH TXT ID.SERVER``. "
"Default is the name as returned by *gethostname(3)*. Same as commandline "
"option :option:`-i`. See hide-identity to set the server to not respond "
"to such queries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:182
msgid "version: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:179
msgid ""
"Returns the specified version string when asked for ``CH TXT "
"version.server``, and ``version.bind`` queries. Default is the compiled "
"package version. See hide-version to set the server to not respond to "
"such queries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:188
msgid "nsid: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:185
msgid ""
"Add the specified nsid to the EDNS section of the answer when queried "
"with an NSID EDNS enabled packet. As a sequence of hex characters or with"
" ascii\\_ prefix and then an ascii string. Same as commandline option "
":option:`-I`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:192
msgid "logfile: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:191
msgid ""
"Log messages to the logfile. The default is to log to stderr and syslog "
"(with facility LOG_DAEMON). Same as commandline option :option:`-l`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:198
msgid "log-only-syslog: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:195
msgid ""
"Log messages only to syslog. Useful with systemd so that print to stderr "
"does not cause duplicate log strings in journald. Before syslog has been "
"opened, the server uses stderr. Stderr is also used if syslog is not "
"available. Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:202
msgid "server-count: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:201
msgid ""
"Start this many NSD servers. Default is 1. Same as commandline option "
":option:`-N`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:205
msgid "cpu-affinity: <number> <number> ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:205
msgid "Overall CPU affinity for NSD server(s). Default is no affinity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:210
msgid "server-N-cpu-affinity: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:208
msgid ""
"Bind NSD server specified by N to a specific core. Default is to have "
"affinity set to every core specified in cpu-affinity. This setting only "
"takes effect if cpu-affinity is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:215
msgid "xfrd-cpu-affinity: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:213
msgid ""
"Bind xfrd to a specific core. Default is to have affinity set to every "
"core specified in cpu-affinity. This setting only takes effect if cpu-"
"affinity is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:219
msgid "tcp-count: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:218
msgid ""
"The maximum number of concurrent, active TCP connections by each server. "
"Default is 100. Same as commandline option :option:`-n`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:223
msgid "tcp-reject-overflow: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:222
msgid ""
"If set to yes, TCP connections made beyond the maximum set by tcp-count "
"will be dropped immediately (accepted and closed). Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:227
msgid "tcp-query-count: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:226
msgid ""
"The maximum number of queries served on a single TCP connection. Default "
"is 0, meaning there is no maximum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:231
msgid "tcp-timeout: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:230
msgid ""
"Overrides the default TCP timeout. This also affects zone transfers over "
"TCP. The default is 120 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:238
msgid "tcp-mss: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:234
msgid ""
"Maximum segment size (MSS) of TCP socket on which the server responds to "
"queries. Value lower than common MSS on Ethernet (1220 for example) will "
"address path MTU problem. Note that not all platform supports socket "
"option to set MSS (TCP_MAXSEG). Default is system default MSS determined "
"by interface MTU and negotiation between server and client."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:246
msgid "outgoing-tcp-mss: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:241
msgid ""
"Maximum segment size (MSS) of TCP socket for outgoing XFR request to "
"other namesevers. Value lower than common MSS on Ethernet (1220 for "
"example) will address path MTU problem. Note that not all platform "
"supports socket option to set MSS (TCP_MAXSEG). Default is system default"
" MSS determined by interface MTU and negotiation between NSD and other "
"servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:249
msgid "ipv4-edns-size: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:249
msgid "Preferred EDNS buffer size for IPv4. Default 1232."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:252
msgid "ipv6-edns-size: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:252
msgid "Preferred EDNS buffer size for IPv6. Default 1232."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:258
msgid "pidfile: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:255
msgid ""
"Use the pid file instead of the platform specific default, usually "
":file:`/var/run/nsd.pid`. Same as commandline option :option:`-P`. With "
"``\"\"`` there is no pidfile, for some startup management setups, where a"
" pidfile is not useful to have."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:262
msgid "port: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:261
msgid ""
"Answer queries on the specified port. Default is 53. Same as commandline "
"option :option:`-p`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:266
msgid "statistics: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:265
msgid ""
"If not present no statistics are dumped. Statistics are produced every "
"number seconds. Same as commandline option :option:`-s`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:275
msgid "chroot: <directory>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:269
msgid ""
"NSD will chroot on startup to the specified directory. Note that if "
"elsewhere in the configuration you specify an absolute pathname to a file"
" inside the chroot, you have to prepend the chroot path. That way, you "
"can switch the chroot option on and off without having to modify anything"
" else in the configuration. Set the value to ``\"\"`` (the empty string) "
"to disable the chroot. By default ``\"\"`` is used. Same as commandline "
"option :option:`-t`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:279
msgid "username: <username>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:278
msgid ""
"After binding the socket, drop user privileges and assume the username. "
"Can be username, id or id.gid. Same as commandline option :option:`-u`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:288
msgid "zonesdir: <directory>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:282
msgid ""
"Change the working directory to the specified directory before accessing "
"zone files. Also, NSD will access **database**, **zonelist-file**, "
"**logfile**, **pidfile**, **xfrdfile**, **xfrdir**, **server-key-file**, "
"**server-cert-file**, **control-key-file** and **control-cert-file** "
"relative to this directory. Set the value to ``\"\"`` (the empty string) "
"to disable the change of working directory. By default "
":file:`\"/etc/nsd\"` is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:291
msgid "difffile: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:291
msgid "Ignored, for compatibility with NSD3 config files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:300
msgid "xfrdfile: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:294
msgid ""
"The soa timeout and zone transfer daemon in NSD will save its state to "
"this file. State is read back after a restart. The state file can be "
"deleted without too much harm, but timestamps of zones will be gone. If "
"it is configured as ``\"\"``, the state file is not used, all slave zones"
" are checked for updates upon startup. For more details see the section "
"on zone expiry behavior of NSD. Default is "
":file:`/var/db/nsd/xfrd.state`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:305
msgid "xfrdir: <directory>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:303
msgid ""
"The zone transfers are stored here before they are processed. A directory"
" is created here that is removed when NSD exits. Default is :file:`/tmp`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:312
msgid "xfrd-reload-timeout: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:308
msgid ""
"If this value is -1, xfrd will not trigger a reload after a zone "
"transfer. If positive xfrd will trigger a reload after a zone transfer, "
"then it will wait for the number of seconds before it will trigger a new "
"reload. Setting this value throttles the reloads to once per the number "
"of seconds. The default is 1 second."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:328
msgid "verbosity: <level>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:315
msgid ""
"This value specifies the verbosity level for (non-debug) logging. Default"
" is 0. 1 gives more information about incoming notifies and zone "
"transfers. 2 lists soft warnings that are encountered. 3 prints more "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:320
msgid ""
"Verbosity 0 will print warnings and errors, and other events that are "
"important to keep NSD running."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:323
msgid ""
"Verbosity 1 prints additionally messages of interest. Successful "
"notifies, successful incoming zone transfer (the zone is updated), failed"
" incoming zone transfers or the inability to process zone updates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:327
msgid ""
"Verbosity 2 prints additionally soft errors, like connection resets over "
"TCP. And notify refusal, and axfr request refusals."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:332
msgid "hide-version: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:331
msgid ""
"Prevent NSD from replying with the version string on CHAOS class queries."
" Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:336
msgid "hide-identity: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:335
msgid ""
"Prevent NSD from replying with the identity string on CHAOS class "
"queries. Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:340
msgid "drop-updates: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:339
msgid ""
"If set to yes, drop received packets with the UPDATE opcode. Default is "
"no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:344
msgid "use-systemd: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:343
msgid ""
"This option is deprecated and ignored. If compiled with libsystemd, NSD "
"signals readiness to systemd and use of the option is not necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:349
msgid "log-time-ascii: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:347
msgid ""
"Log time in ascii, if \"no\" then in seconds epoch. Default is yes. This "
"chooses the format when logging to file. The print- out via syslog has a "
"timestamp formatted by syslog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:354
msgid "round-robin: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:352
msgid ""
"Enable round robin rotation of records in the answer. This changes the "
"order of records in the answer and this may balance load across them. The"
" default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:362
msgid "minimal-responses: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:357
msgid ""
"Enable minimal responses for smaller answers. This makes pack- ets "
"smaller. Extra data is only added for referrals, when it is really "
"necessary. This is different from the --enable-minimal-responses "
"configure time option, that reduces packets, but ex- actly to the "
"fragmentation length, the nsd.conf option reduces packets as small as "
"possible. The default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:367
msgid "confine-to-zone: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:365
msgid ""
"If set to yes, additional information will not be added to the response "
"if the apex zone of the additional information does not match the apex "
"zone of the initial query (E.G. CNAME resolution). Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:374
msgid "refuse-any: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:370
msgid ""
"Refuse queries of type ANY. This is useful to stop query floods trying to"
" get large responses. Note that rrl ratelimiting also has type ANY as a "
"ratelimiting type. It sends truncation in response to UDP type ANY "
"queries, and it allows TCP type ANY queries like normal. The default is "
"no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:380
msgid "zonefiles-check: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:377
msgid ""
"Make NSD check the mtime of zone files on start and sighup. If you "
"disable it it starts faster (less disk activity in case of a lot of "
"zones). The default is yes. The nsd-control reload command reloads zone "
"files regardless of this option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:389
msgid "zonefiles-write: <seconds>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:383
msgid ""
"Write changed secondary zones to their zonefile every N seconds. If the "
"zone (pattern) configuration has ``\"\"`` zonefile, it is not written. "
"Zones that have received zone transfer updates are written to their "
"zonefile. Default is 0 (disabled) when there is a database, and 3600 (1 "
"hour) when database is ``\"\"``. The database also commits zone transfer "
"contents. You can configure it away from the default by putting the "
"config statement for zone-files-write: after the database: statement in "
"the config file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:393
msgid "rrl-size: <numbuckets>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:392
msgid ""
"This option gives the size of the hashtable. Default 1000000. More "
"buckets use more memory, and reduce the chance of hash collisions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:408
msgid "rrl-ratelimit: <qps>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:396
msgid ""
"The max qps allowed (from one query source). Default is on (with a "
"suggested 200 qps). If set to 0 then it is disabled (unlimited rate), "
"also set the whitelist-ratelimit to 0 to disable rate-limit processing. "
"If you set verbosity to 2 the blocked and unblocked subnets are logged. "
"Blocked queries are blocked and some receive TCP fallback replies. Once "
"the rate limit is reached, NSD begins dropping responses. However, one in"
" every \"rrl-slip\" number of responses is allowed, with the TC bit set. "
"If slip is set to 2, the outgoing response rate will be halved. If it's "
"set to 3, the outgoing response rate will be one-third, and so on. If you"
" set rrl-slip to 10, traffic is reduced to 1/10th. Ratelimit options rrl-"
"ratelimit, rrl-size and rrl-whitelist-ratelimit are updated when nsd-"
"control reconfig is done (also the zone-specific ratelimit options are "
"updated)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:415
msgid "rrl-slip: <numpackets>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:411
msgid ""
"This option controls the number of packets discarded before we send back "
"a SLIP response (a response with \"truncated\" bit set to one). 0 "
"disables the sending of SLIP packets, 1 means every query will get a SLIP"
" response. Default is 2, cuts traffic in half and legit users have a fair"
" chance to get a +TC response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:418
msgid "rrl-ipv4-prefix-length: <subnet>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:418
msgid "IPv4 prefix length. Addresses are grouped by netblock. Default 24."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:421
msgid "rrl-ipv6-prefix-length: <subnet>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:421
msgid "IPv6 prefix length. Addresses are grouped by netblock. Default 64."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:427
msgid "rrl-whitelist-ratelimit: <qps>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:424
msgid ""
"The max qps for query sorts for a source, which have been whitelisted. "
"Default on (with a suggested 2000 qps). With the rrl-whitelist option you"
" can set specific queries to receive this qps limit instead of the normal"
" limit. With the value 0 the rate is unlimited."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:430
msgid "answer-cookie: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:430
msgid ""
"Enable to answer to requests containig DNS Cookies as specified in "
":RFC:`7873`. Default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:438
msgid "cookie-secret: <128 bit hex string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:433
msgid ""
"Servers in an anycast deployment need to be able to verify each other's "
"DNS Server Cookies. For this they need to share the secret used to "
"construct and verify the DNS Cookies. Default is a 128 bits random secret"
" generated at startup time. This option is ignored if a **cookie-secret-"
"file** is present. In that case the secrets from that file are used in "
"DNS Cookie calculations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:450
msgid "cookie-secret-file: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:441
msgid ""
"File from which the secrets are read used in DNS Cookie calculations. "
"When this file exists, the secrets in this file are used and the secret "
"specified by the **cookie-secret** option is ignored. Default is "
":file:`/etc/nsd/nsd_cookiesecrets.txt`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:446
msgid ""
"The content of this file must be manipulated with the "
"**add_cookie_secret**, **drop_cookie_secret** and "
"**activate_cookie_secret** commands to the :manpage:`nsd-control(8)` "
"tool. Please see that manpage how to perform a safe cookie secret "
"rollover."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:462
msgid "tls-service-key: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:453
msgid ""
"If enabled, the server provides TLS service on TCP sockets with the TLS "
"service port number. The port number (853) is configured with tls-port. "
"To turn it on, create an interface: option line in config with @port "
"appended to the IP-address. This creates the extra socket on which the "
"DNS over TLS service is provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:459
msgid ""
"The file is the private key for the TLS session. The public certificate "
"is in the tls-service-pem file. Default is ``\"\"``, turned off. Requires"
" a restart (a reload is not enough) if changed, because the private key "
"is read while root permissions are held and before chroot (if any)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:466
msgid "tls-service-pem: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:465
msgid ""
"The public key certificate pem file for the tls service. Default is "
"``\"\"``, turned off."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:481
msgid "tls-service-ocsp: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:469
msgid ""
"The ocsp pem file for the tls service, for OCSP stapling. Default is "
"``\"\"``, turned off. An external process prepares and updates the OCSP "
"stapling data. Like this,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:486
msgid "tls-port: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:484
msgid ""
"The port number on which to provide TCP TLS service, default is 853, only"
" interfaces configured with that port number as @number get DNS over TLS "
"service."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:492
msgid "tls-cert-bundle: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:489
msgid ""
"If null or ``\"\"``, the default verify locations are used. Set it to the"
" certificate bundle file, for example :file:`\"/etc/pki/tls/certs/ca-"
"bundle.crt\"`. These certificates are used for authenticating Transfer "
"over TLS (XoT) connections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:495
msgid "Remote Control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:497
msgid ""
"The **remote-control:** clause is used to set options for using the "
":manpage:`nsd-control(8)` tool to give commands to the running NSD "
"server. It is disabled by default, and listens for localhost by default. "
"It uses TLS over TCP where the server and client authenticate to each "
"other with self-signed certificates. The self-signed certificates can be "
"generated with the *nsd-control-setup* tool. The key files are read by "
"NSD before the chroot and before dropping user permissions, so they can "
"be outside the chroot and readable by the superuser only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:507
msgid "control-enable: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:507
msgid "Enable remote control, default is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:526
msgid "control-interface: <ip4 or ip6 | interface name | absolute path>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:510
msgid ""
"NSD will bind to the listed addresses to service control requests (on "
"TCP). Can be given multiple times to bind multiple ip-addresses. Use "
"0.0.0.0 and ::0 to service the wildcard interface. If none are given NSD "
"listens to the localhost 127.0.0.1 and ::1 interfaces for control, if "
"control is enabled with control-enable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:520
msgid ""
"With an absolute path, a unix local named pipe is used for control. The "
"file is created with user and group that is configured and access bits "
"are set to allow members of the group access. Further access can be "
"controlled by setting permissions on the directory containing the control"
" socket file. The key and cert files are not used when control is via the"
" named pipe, because access control is via file and directory permission."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:529
msgid "control-port: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:529
msgid "The port number for remote control service. 8952 by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:535
msgid "server-key-file: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:532
msgid ""
"Path to the server private key, by default "
":file:`/etc/nsd/nsd_server.key`. This file is generated by the nsd-"
"control-setup utility. This file is used by the nsd server, but not by "
"*nsd-control*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:541
msgid "server-cert-file: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:538
msgid ""
"Path to the server self signed certificate, by default "
":file:`/etc/nsd/nsd_server.pem`. This file is generated by the *nsd-"
"control-setup* utility. This file is used by the nsd server, and also by "
"*nsd-control*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:546
msgid "control-key-file: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:544
msgid ""
"Path to the control client private key, by default "
":file:`/etc/nsd/nsd_control.key`. This file is generated by the *nsd-"
"control-setup* utility. This file is used by *nsd-control*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:552
msgid "control-cert-file: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:549
msgid ""
"Path to the control client certificate, by default "
":file:`/etc/nsd/nsd_control.pem`. This certificate has to be signed with "
"the server certificate. This file is generated by the *nsd-control-setup*"
" utility. This file is used by *nsd-control*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:555
msgid "Pattern Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:557
msgid ""
"The **pattern:** clause is used to denote a set of options to apply to "
"some zones. The same zone options as for a zone are allowed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:563
#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:590
#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:779
#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:806
msgid "name: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:561
msgid ""
"The name of the pattern. This is a (case sensitive) string. The pattern "
"names that start with \"_implicit_\" are used internally for zones that "
"have no pattern (they are defined in *nsd.conf* directly)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:567
#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:753
msgid "include-pattern: <pattern-name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:566
msgid ""
"The options from the given pattern are included at this point in this "
"pattern. The referenced pattern must be defined above this one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:574
msgid "<zone option>: <value>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:570
msgid ""
"The zone options such as **zonefile**, **allow-query**, **allow-notify**,"
" **request-xfr**, **allow-axfr-fallback**, **notify**, **notify-retry**, "
"**provide-xfr**, **zonestats**, and **outgoing-interface** can be given. "
"They are applied to the patterns and zones that include this pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:577
msgid "Zone Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:579
msgid ""
"For every zone the options need to be specified in one **zone:** clause. "
"The access control list elements can be given multiple times to add "
"multiple servers. These elements need to be added explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:583
msgid ""
"For zones that are configured in the *nsd.conf* config file their "
"settings are hardcoded (in an implicit pattern for themselves only) and "
"they cannot be deleted via delzone, but remove them from the config file "
"and repattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:588
msgid ""
"The name of the zone. This is the domain name of the apex of the zone. "
"May end with a ``'.'`` (in FQDN notation). For example \"example.com\", "
"\"sub.example.net.\". This attribute must be present in each zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:614
msgid "zonefile: <filename>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:593
msgid ""
"The file containing the zone information. If this attribute is present it"
" is used to read and write the zone contents. If the attribute is absent "
"it prevents writing out of the zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:597
msgid ""
"The string is processed so that one string can be used (in a pattern) for"
" a lot of different zones. If the label or character does not exist the "
"percent-character is replaced with a period for output (i.e. for the "
"third character in a two letter domain name)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:602
#, python-format
msgid "**%s** is replaced with the zone name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:604
msgid "**%1** is replaced with the first character of the zone name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:606
msgid "**%2** is replaced with the second character of the zone name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:608
msgid "**%3** is replaced with the third character of the zone name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:610
msgid "**%z** is replaced with the toplevel domain name of the zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:612
msgid "**%y** is replaced with the next label under the toplevel domain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:614
#, python-format
msgid "**%x** is replaced with the next-next label under the toplevel domain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:630
msgid "allow-query: <ip-spec> <key-name | NOKEY | BLOCKED>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:617
msgid ""
"Access control list. When at least one **allow-query** option is "
"specified, then the in the **allow-query** options specified addresses "
"are are allowed to query the server for the zone. Queries from unlisted "
"or specifically BLOCKED addresses are discarded. If NOKEY is given no "
"TSIG signature is required. BLOCKED supersedes other entries, other "
"entries are scanned for a match in the order of the statements. Without "
"**allow-query** options, queries are allowed from any IP address without "
"TSIG key (which is the default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:626
msgid ""
"The ip-spec is either a plain IP address (IPv4 or IPv6), or can be a "
"subnet of the form ``1.2.3.4/24``, or masked like "
"``1.2.3.4&255.255.255.0`` or a range of the form ``1.2.3.4-1.2.3.25``. "
"Note the ip-spec ranges do not use spaces around the ``/``, ``&``, ``@`` "
"and ``-`` symbols."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:645
msgid "allow-notify: <ip-spec> <key-name | NOKEY | BLOCKED>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:633
msgid ""
"Access control list. The listed (primary) address is allowed to send "
"notifies to this (secondary) server. Notifies from unlisted or "
"specifically BLOCKED addresses are discarded. If NOKEY is given no TSIG "
"signature is required. BLOCKED supersedes other entries, other entries "
"are scanned for a match in the order of the statements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:639
msgid ""
"The ip-spec is either a plain IP address (IPv4 or IPv6), or can be a "
"subnet of the form ``1.2.3.4/24``, or masked like "
"``1.2.3.4&255.255.255.0`` or a range of the form ``1.2.3.4-1.2.3.25``. A "
"port number can be added using a suffix of @number, for example "
"``1.2.3.4@5300`` or ``1.2.3.4/24@5300`` for port 5300. Note the ip-spec "
"ranges do not use spaces around the ``/``, ``&``, ``@`` and ``-`` "
"symbols."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:670
msgid "request-xfr: [AXFR|UDP] <ip-address> <key-name | NOKEY> [tls-auth-name]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:648
msgid ""
"Access control list. The listed address (the master) is queried for "
"AXFR/IXFR on update. A port number can be added using a suffix of "
"@number, for example ``1.2.3.4@5300``. The specified key is used during "
"AXFR/IXFR. If tls-auth-name is included, the specified tls-auth clause "
"will be used to perform authenticated XFR-over-TLS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:654
msgid ""
"If the AXFR option is given, the server will not be contacted with IXFR "
"queries but only AXFR requests will be made to the server. This allows an"
" NSD secondary to have a master server that runs NSD. If the AXFR option "
"is left out then both IXFR and AXFR requests are made to the master "
"server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:660
msgid ""
"If the UDP option is given, the secondary will use UDP to trans- mit the "
"IXFR requests. You should deploy TSIG when allowing UDP transport, to "
"authenticate notifies and zone transfers. Otherwise, NSD is more "
"vulnerable for Kaminsky-style attacks. If the UDP option is left out then"
" IXFR will be transmitted using TCP."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:666
msgid ""
"If a tls-auth-name is given then TLS (by default on port 853) will be "
"used for all zone transfers for the zone. If authentication of the master"
" based on the specified tls-auth authentication information fails, the "
"XFR request will not be sent. Support for TLS 1.3 is required for XFR-"
"over-TLS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:675
msgid "allow-axfr-fallback: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:673
msgid ""
"This option should be accompanied by request-xfr. It (dis)allows NSD (as "
"secondary) to fallback to AXFR if the primary name server does not "
"support IXFR. Default is yes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:681
msgid "size-limit-xfr: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:678
msgid ""
"This option should be accompanied by request-xfr. It specifies XFR "
"temporary file size limit. It can be used to stop very large zone "
"retrieval, that could otherwise use up a lot of memory and disk space. If"
" this option is 0, unlimited. Default value is 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:688
msgid "notify: <ip-address> <key-name | NOKEY>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:684
msgid ""
"Access control list. The listed address (a secondary) is notified of "
"updates to this zone. A port number can be added using a suffix of "
"@number, for example ``1.2.3.4@5300``. The specified key is used to sign "
"the notify. Only on secondary configurations will NSD be able to detect "
"zone updates (as it gets notified itself, or refreshes after a time)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:692
msgid "notify-retry: <number>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:691
msgid ""
"This option should be accompanied by notify. It sets the number of "
"retries when sending notifies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:710
msgid "provide-xfr: <ip-spec> <key-name | NOKEY | BLOCKED>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:695
msgid ""
"Access control list. The listed address (a secondary) is allowed to "
"request AXFR from this server. Zone data will be provided to the address."
" The specified key is used during AXFR. For unlisted or BLOCKED addresses"
" no data is provided, requests are discarded. BLOCKED supersedes other "
"entries, other entries are scanned for a match in the order of the "
"statements. NSD provides AXFR for its secondaries, but IXFR is not "
"implemented (IXFR is implemented for request-xfr, but not for provide-"
"xfr)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:704
msgid ""
"The ip-spec is either a plain IP address (IPv4 or IPv6), or can be a "
"subnet of the form ``1.2.3.4/24``, or masked like "
"``1.2.3.4&255.255.255.0`` or a range of the form ``1.2.3.4-1.2.3.25``. A "
"port number can be added using a suffix of @number, for example "
"``1.2.3.4@5300`` or ``1.2.3.4/24@5300`` for port 5300. Note the ip-spec "
"ranges do not use spaces around the the ``/``, ``&``, ``@`` and ``-`` "
"symbols."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:717
msgid "outgoing-interface: <ip-address>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:713
msgid ""
"Access control list. The listed address is used to request AXFR|IXFR (in "
"case of a secondary) or used to send notifies (in case of a primary)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:716
msgid ""
"The ip-address is a plain IP address (IPv4 or IPv6). A port number can be"
" added using a suffix of @number, for example ``1.2.3.4@5300``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:722
msgid "max-refresh-time: <seconds>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:720
msgid ""
"Limit refresh time for secondary zones. This is the timer which checks to"
" see if the zone has to be refetched when it expires. Normally the value "
"from the SOA record is used, but this option restricts that value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:725
msgid "min-refresh-time: <seconds>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:725
msgid "Limit refresh time for secondary zones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:731
msgid "max-retry-time: <seconds>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:728
msgid ""
"Limit retry time for secondary zones. This is the timer which retries "
"after a failed fetch attempt for the zone. Normally the value from the "
"SOA record is used, followed by an exponential backoff, but this option "
"restricts that value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:734
msgid "min-retry-time: <seconds>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:734
msgid "Limit retry time for secondary zones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:742
msgid "min-expire-time: <seconds or refresh+retry+1>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:737
msgid ""
"Limit expire time for secondary zones. The value can be expressed either "
"by a number of seconds, or the string \"refresh+retry+1\". With the "
"latter the expire time will be lower bound to the refresh plus the retry "
"value from the SOA record, plus 1. The refresh and retry values will be "
"subject to the bounds configured with max-refresh-time, min-refresh-time,"
" max-retry-time and min-retry-time if given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:749
msgid "zonestats: <name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:745
#, python-format
msgid ""
"When compiled with ``--enable-zone-stats`` NSD can collect statistics per"
" zone. This name gives the group where statistics are added to. The "
"groups are output from nsd-control stats and stats_noreset. Default is "
"``\"\"``. You can use ``\"%s\"`` to use the name of the zone to track its"
" statistics. If not compiled in, the option can be given but is ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:752
msgid ""
"The options from the given pattern are included at this point. The "
"referenced pattern must be defined above this zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:763
msgid "rrl-whitelist: <rrltype>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:756
msgid ""
"This option causes queries of this rrltype to be whitelisted, for this "
"zone. They receive the whitelist-ratelimit. You can give multiple lines, "
"each enables a new rrltype to be whitelisted for the zone. Default has "
"none whitelisted. The rrl-type is the query classification that the NSD "
"RRL employs to make different types not interfere with one another. The "
"types are logged in the loglines when a subnet is blocked (in verbosity "
"2). The RRL classification types are: nxdomain, error, referral, any, "
"rrsig, wildcard, nodata, dnskey, positive, all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:768
msgid "multi-master-check: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:766
msgid ""
"Default no. If enabled, checks all masters for the last version. It uses "
"the higher version of all the configured masters. Useful if you have "
"multiple masters that have different version numbers served."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:771
msgid "Key Declarations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:773
msgid ""
"The **key:** clause establishes a key for use in access control lists. It"
" has the following attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:777
msgid ""
"The key name. Used to refer to this key in the access control list. The "
"key name has to be correct for tsig to work. This is because the key name"
" is output on the wire."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:785
msgid "algorithm: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:782
msgid ""
"Authentication algorithm for this key. Such as hmac-md5, hmac-sha1, hmac-"
"sha224, hmac-sha256, hmac-sha384 and hmac-sha512. Can also be abbreviated"
" as 'sha1', 'sha256'. Default is sha256. Algorithms are only available "
"when they were compiled in (available in the crypto library)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:795
msgid "secret: <base64 blob>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:788
msgid ""
"The base64 encoded shared secret. It is possible to put the **secret:** "
"declaration (and base64 blob) into a different file, and then to "
"**include:** that file. In this way the key secret and the rest of the "
"configuration file, which may have different security policies, can be "
"split apart. The content of the secret is the agreed base64 secret "
"content. To make it up, enter a password (its length must be a multiple "
"of 4 characters, A-Za-z0-9), or use dev-random output through a base64 "
"encode filter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:798
msgid "TLS Auth Declarations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:800
msgid ""
"The **tls-auth:** clause establishes authentication attributes to use "
"when authenticating the far end of an outgoing TLS connection used in "
"access control lists for XFR-over-TLS. It has the following attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:805
msgid ""
"The tls-auth name. Used to refer to this TLS authentication information "
"in the access control list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:809
msgid "auth-domain-name: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:809
msgid "The authentication domain name as defined in :RFC:`8310`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:815
msgid "client-cert: <file name of clientcert.pem>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:812
msgid ""
"If you want to use mutual TLS authentication, this is where the client "
"certificates can be configured that NSD uses to connect to the upstream "
"server to download the zone. The client public key pem cert file can be "
"configured here. Also configure a private key with client-key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:819
msgid "client-key: <file name of clientkey.key>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:818
msgid ""
"If you want to use mutual TLS authentication, the private key file can be"
" configured here for the client authentication."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:826
msgid "client-key-pw: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:822
msgid ""
"If the client-key file uses a password to decrypt the key before it can "
"be used, then the password can be specified here as a string. It is "
"possible to include other config files with the include: option, and this"
" can be used to move that sensitive data to another file, if you wish."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:829
msgid "DNSTAP Logging Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:831
msgid ""
"DNSTAP support, when compiled in, is enabled in the **dnstap:** section. "
"This starts a collector process that writes the log information to the "
"destination."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:837
msgid "dnstap-enable: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:835
msgid ""
"If dnstap is enabled. Default no. If yes, it connects to the dnstap "
"server and if any of the dnstap-log-..-messages options is enabled it "
"sends logs for those messages to the server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:841
msgid "dnstap-socket-path: <file name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:840
msgid ""
"Sets the unix socket file name for connecting to the server that is "
"listening on that socket. Default is :file:`\"/var/run/nsd-"
"dnstap.sock\"`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:845
msgid "dnstap-send-identity: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:844
msgid ""
"If enabled, the server identity is included in the log messages. Default "
"is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:849
msgid "dnstap-send-version: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:848
msgid ""
"If enabled, the server version if included in the log messages. Default "
"is no."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:853
msgid "dnstap-identity: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:852
msgid ""
"The identity to send with messages, if ``\"\"`` the hostname is used. "
"Default is ``\"\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:857
msgid "dnstap-version: <string>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:856
msgid ""
"The version to send with messages, if ``\"\"`` the package version is "
"used. Default is ``\"\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:861
msgid "dnstap-log-auth-query-messages: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:860
msgid ""
"Enable to log auth query messages. Default is no. These are client "
"queries to NSD."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:865
msgid "dnstap-log-auth-response-messages: <yes or no>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:864
msgid ""
"Enable to log auth response messages. Default is no. These are responses "
"from NSD to clients."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:868
msgid "NSD Configuration for BIND9 Hackers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:870
msgid ""
"BIND9 is a name server implementation with its own configuration file "
"format, *named.conf(5)*. BIND9 types zones as 'Master' or 'Slave'."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:874
msgid "Slave zones"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:875
msgid ""
"For a slave zone, the master servers are listed. The master servers are "
"queried for zone data, and are listened to for update notifications. In "
"NSD these two properties need to be configured separately, by listing the"
" master address in allow-notify and request-xfr statements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:880
msgid ""
"In BIND9 you only need to provide allow-notify elements for any extra "
"sources of notifications (i.e. the operators), NSD needs to have allow-"
"notify for both masters and operators. BIND9 allows additional transfer "
"sources, in NSD you list those as request-xfr."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:885
msgid "Here is an example of a slave zone in BIND9 syntax."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:908
msgid ""
"For NSD, DNSSEC is enabled automatically for zones that are signed. The "
"**dnssec-enable** statement in the options clause is not needed. In NSD "
"keys are associated with an IP address in the access control list "
"statement, therefore the **server{}** statement is not needed. Below is "
"the same example in an NSD config file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:929
msgid ""
"Notice that the master is listed twice, once to allow it to send notifies"
" to this slave server and once to tell the slave server where to look for"
" updates zone data. More allow-notify and request-xfr lines can be added "
"to specify more masters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:934
msgid ""
"It is possible to specify extra allow-notify lines for addresses that are"
" also allowed to send notifications to this slave server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:938
msgid "Master zones"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/manpages/nsd.conf.rst:940
msgid ""
"For a master zone in BIND9, the slave servers are listed. These slave "
"servers are sent notifications of updated and are allowed to request "
"transfer of the zone data. In NSD these two properties need to be "
"configured separately."
msgstr ""

